data: Marauders (MRD) are Lominsan pirates who rely on brute force to wield mighty battle axes. Warriors (WAR) call upon the spirit of the inner beast to unlock their true strength.

Lancers (LNC) form the corps of Gridania's Wood Wailers, a militia tasked with defending the city-state using their spears. Dragoons (DRG) are the sworn enemies of the dragons who threaten Ishgard and call upon their legendary jumping ability to protect it.

Archers (ARC) represent the Gods' Quiver, a Gridanian police force which guards the forest from outside intrusion. Bards (BRD) are expert marksmen who have developed songs to invigorate their allies in battle.

data: Some of the oxalate in urine is produced by the body. Calcium and oxalate in the diet play a part but are not the only factors that affect the formation of calcium oxalate stones. Dietary oxalate is an organic molecule found in many vegetables, fruits, and nuts. Calcium from bone may also play a role in kidney stone formation.
Diets rich in animal proteins and purines: substances found naturally in all food but especially in organ meats, fish, and shellfish.
Preventing struvite stones depends on staying infection-free. Diet has not been shown to affect struvite stone formation.
Cystine, an amino acid (one of the building blocks of protein), leaks through the kidneys and into the urine to form crystals.

data: The bidders look for bargains in Trenton, New Jersey. Chris and Tad take a gamble on a $475 locker and encounter a vintage firework device. A new buyer named "Big Steve", who owns a massive flea market, enters the picture and purchases an $1,100 room on a unit containing gumball machines and receives a great amount of cash. Joe P. buys a room for $425 containing furniture, a few little mystery items, and then finds old vintage hearing aids. Mike and the team of Candy and Courtney don't purchase a unit at the auction.

table-1223-886.caption: Timeline
data: A mosque was built by Mukhtar ibn Abu `Ubayd ath-Thaqafi on the spot and a dome was created over the grave. Over the dome he fixed a green flag. Two entrance gates were made for the mosque. He also settled several families around the enclosure.
Once again the mausoleum was destroyed.
The shrine was rebuilt by the Alid council and two minarets were constructed on either side of the grave. Two entrance gates for the shrine were also constructed.
The two minarets were reconstructed of gold by Sultan Ahmad ibn `Uways. The courtyard was also extended.
The western minaret was rebuilt by Dr. Syedna Taher Saifuddin. He spent a huge amount generously for the purpose of gold plating all the Min’ar. From top to bottom, pure gold was installed.
Repairs to the shrine from the damage done in 1991 are finally completed.
December 15: A bomb detonated near the gate of the shrine, killing at least 7 people and injuring 31 others.
December: Construction work began on building a roof over the courtyard of the mosque, with hopes of creating a second floor and expanding the mosque.
September 11: A bomb was detonated 800m from the shrine, killing one woman and injuring 12 others.

table-1223-748.caption: March
data: Unidentified gunmen ambushed a Syrian Army convoy escorted by Iraqi soldiers, killing 51 Syrians and 13 Iraqis. The well-planned assault took place in Akashat, near the desert border between the two nations. The Islamic State of Iraq claimed responsibility for the attack on March 11.

A coordinated series of attacks near the Justice Ministry in Baghdad left 7 insurgents and 24 civilians dead, while 57 others were wounded. Various other incidents across the country killed 2 and injured 15.

A rare car bombing struck Basra, killing 10 civilians and injuring 19 others. The blast took place close to a bus station on the outskirts of Iraq's second largest city. An earlier bombing near a tax department injured 5 people.
The Islamist al-Shabaab group claimed responsibility for a car bombing near Mogadishu's National Theater that killed 10 and wounded 20 others, including the city's intelligence chief Khalif Ereg.
A suicide bomber attacked a bus station in a predominantly Christian area of Kano, killing 41 passengers and injuring dozens more.
A suicide bomber detonated his vest at a checkpoint near the US consulate in Peshawar, killing 10 people and injuring 31 others, most of them civilians.

table-1223-751.caption: June
data: A suicide bomber on a motorcycle detonated his explosives near a military convoy and government offices, killing two U.S. soldiers, an Afghan police officer and 10 children from a nearby school. At least twenty others were injured by the blast.

A group of militants hiding automatic weapons inside a coffin prepared for burial attacked a government militia checkpoint in the northern city of Maiduguri, killing 13 people before being shot during an escape attempt.

Two suicide bombers detonated their explosives-laden vehicles in front of Afghanistan's Supreme Court building in a heavily fortified area of the capital Kabul. The attack, which targeted buses with court employees, killed at least 17 people and left dozens more injured.

A suicide bomber blew himself up at a Shiite mosque in a Peshawar's Gulshan neighborhood, killing at least 15 and injuring dozens more. The perpetrators first gunned down a police officer and a security guard, before the suicide bomber went into the mosque.
